<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="yes"?>
<!--
  The application manifest — convergence plan A3, completing a job A1 deliberately left here.

  activeCodePage=UTF-8 is the point of this file. Every narrow string this program takes from the
  OS — argv, getenv, and everything it then hands to std::ifstream and std::filesystem::path — is
  decoded through the process ANSI code page, which is a per-machine locale setting (1251 here, 1252
  on a Western install, 932 on a Japanese one). Pinning it to UTF-8 makes one binary read one disk
  the same way everywhere instead of differently per install. Windows 10 1903+ honours it; older
  Windows ignores it and behaves exactly as before, so there is nothing to fall back to.

  ⚠️ WHAT WAS AND WAS NOT DEMONSTRATED (2026-07-20). Do not upgrade this claim without new
  measurement. Two attempts to show a behavioural difference on this box BOTH came back with the
  control passing:
    - a Cyrillic+Japanese POCKETTRACKER_HOME: both builds created the folder tree correctly;
    - opening `日本語のうた.ptp` by argv, straight into std::ifstream: both builds read it,
      neither printed main.cpp's "cannot read".
  This machine's ACP is 1251, which cannot represent 日本語, so the control was expected to fail and
  did not — meaning the mechanism is not the simple one assumed, and MSVC's filesystem picks its
  code page at runtime (`__std_fs_code_page`) rather than the fixed ACP that std_filesystem.cpp's
  own comment describes.

  It is kept because it is Microsoft's documented setting for exactly this class of bug, it is inert
  where unsupported, and A1 chose CP_ACP in `documents_directory()` on the stated expectation that
  this would land (CP_ACP is right on a legacy code page and stays right once the ACP *is* UTF-8).
  But one locale on one machine is not a proof, and "no difference observed here" is not "no
  difference". ⚠️ The open question A1 and this file jointly raise — whether CP_ACP is still the
  correct conversion given what `__std_fs_code_page` actually does — is unanswered and worth a
  session of its own.

  ⚠️ The linker is told NOT to generate its own manifest (/MANIFEST:NO in shell/CMakeLists.txt), or
  there would be two and the embedded one here would be the loser. The trustInfo block below is
  therefore not decoration: it is the asInvoker level the auto-generated manifest used to supply,
  restated so that suppressing it changes nothing else.

  ⚠️ The linker is told NOT to generate its own manifest (/MANIFEST:NO in shell/CMakeLists.txt), or
  there would be two and the embedded one here would be the loser. The trustInfo block below is
  therefore not decoration: it is the asInvoker level the auto-generated manifest used to supply,
  restated so that suppressing it changes nothing else.
--><assembly xmlns="urn:schemas-microsoft-com:asm.v1" manifestVersion="1.0">

  <trustInfo xmlns="urn:schemas-microsoft-com:asm.v3">
    <security>
      <requestedPrivileges>
        <!-- A tracker has no business asking for elevation. -->
        <requestedExecutionLevel level="asInvoker" uiAccess="false"/>
      </requestedPrivileges>
    </security>
  </trustInfo>

  <compatibility xmlns="urn:schemas-microsoft-com:compatibility.v1">
    <application>
      <!-- Windows 10 / 11. Declaring the supported OS is what opts the process in to the
           per-version behaviour below rather than the compatibility-shimmed defaults. -->
      <supportedOS Id="{8e0f7a12-bfb3-4fe8-b9a5-48fd50a15a9a}"/>
    </application>
  </compatibility>

  <application xmlns="urn:schemas-microsoft-com:asm.v3">
    <windowsSettings>
      <activeCodePage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/SMI/2019/WindowsSettings">UTF-8</activeCodePage>
    </windowsSettings>
  </application>

</assembly>
